{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12713"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.75,0.04,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85956"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic after having a blood pressure measurement recorded at 156/94 mmHg. Repeating the measurement at the clinic during the same visit, his blood pressure remains 156/94 mmHg. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a current smoker with a 15-pack-year smoking history and drinks about four cans of beer per week. His urinalysis is negative for both red blood cells and protein. Laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol 5.0 mmol/L (3.0-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL cholesterol 3.5 mmol/L (0.9-2.4) \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting glucose 5.5 mmol/L (3.0-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis ECG is unremarkable. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is booked for ambulatory blood pressure monitoring with follow-up in six weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perindopril","Lifestyle modification","Amlodipine","Hydrochlorothiazide","Perindopril and valsartan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with uncomplicated hypertension and a cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk assessment score of less than 5%, indicating a low risk of developing cardiovascular disease within the next five years. According to Australian guidelines for managing hypertension, low risk patients who present with an initial systolic blood pressure of \u0026lt;160 mmHg can be initially advised to make \u003Cstrong\u003Elifestyle modifications\u003C/strong\u003E with review within two months. These modifications include smoking cessation, diet modifications, regular exercise and weight loss goals. Antihypertensive therapy is recommended for low risk patients who have persistent BP readings \u2265160/100 mmHg despite lifestyle advice.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor, is indicated as a first-line drug for managing hypertension where there are co-morbidities such as renal failure, diabetes, personal or family history of cardiovascular disease, or in those with a moderate to high CVD risk (more than 10%). It would also be indicated if elevated blood pressure persists despite initial lifestyle modification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, while an effective antihypertensive, is not indicated as initial therapy in this patient with uncomplicated hypertension and low CVD risk where lifestyle modifications should be trialed first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E, a thiazide diuretic can be used as a first-line antihypertensive treatment option, though ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are generally preferred. However in this patient with a low CVD risk score, lifestyle modifications should be trialed first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril and valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E are an ACE inhibitor and angiotensin receptor blocker respectively. They both are first-line antihypertensive treatment options separately, but should not be given together in combination as this leads to an increased risk of renal dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lifestyle modifications including smoking cessation, diet and exercise changes and weight loss should be recommended to all patients with hypertension.","Lifestyle modifications and review within two months is an appropriate first line management option for patients with no medical co-morbidities and a low CVD risk."],"references":["National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance. Australian Absolute Cardiovascular Disease Risk Calculator[Internet]. Melbourne: NVDPA; [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85956"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12713"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85956"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T14:42:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T18:28:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5168"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"hea